{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> φρῑκ-ώδης</b>, ες, <br /> <b>attended with shivering,</b> πνρετὸς φ. a fever <b>with shivering fits, ague,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “ἐπιδημίαι” 1.2, 2nd c.AD: Soranus Medicus 1.59; δυσουρία φ. 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “ἀφορισμοί” 3.5; οἱ φ. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<b>those who suffer from such fits,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Coac.” 12, +others\">Refs</a>]; τὸ φ. <b>roughness, unevenness of the skin,</b> as in aguish fits,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 17, compare 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 6.195. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>that causes shuddering</b> or <b>horror, awful, horrible,</b> ὄψις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 1336 (Lyric poetry); τὰ δεινὰ καὶ φ. 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.29 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; φρικώδη κλύειν <b>horrible</b> to hear, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 1202 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; frequently in later Prose, δόξαι φ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Mus.” p.50 \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>] K.; φ. ἄποψις, θέαμα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Mirabilia” 843a16, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Marcellus” 15, Anonymus “Oxy.” 416.9, 4th c.AD: Julianus Imperator “Orationes” 1.31c; τὸ -έστατον τῶν κακῶν ὁ θάνατος 4th-3rd c.BC: Epicurus Philosophus “Epistulae” 3p.61U.; -έστατος ὅρκος “PStrassb.” 48.6 (6th c.AD), etc.: _neuter_ φρικῶδες,\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] as <i>adverb</i>, <b>horribly,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 1216. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__II.b</b></Level4> <b>inspiring religious awe,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Tiberius Gracchus” 21 (_superlative_), 2nd c.AD: Aristides Rhetor 1.256J. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>] <i>adverb</i> <i>superlative</i>, ἁγιώτατα καὶ φρικωδέστατα ἔχειν, of the terrors of a court of justice, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 23.74. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G9664","accentedUnicode":"φρικώδης","shortDef":"a cause for shuddering","mediumDef":"a cause for shuddering","stepGloss":"a cause for shuddering","stepTransliteration":"frikōdēs","_step_Type":"word"}]}